  "text": "Using the findings of these latter studies, the d 18 O analysis of diatoms from Lake Kotokel contributes to a better understanding of the late Quaternary environments and climate history of the region, and to complement the longer records obtained from Lake Baikal deep-water sediments, which suffer from several problems influencing accurate dating and environmental reconstructions. These include the hard-water effect and low organic content [CITATION_1] , partial dissolution of diatoms [CITATION_2] and pollen grains [CITATION_3] , long residence time and, thus, lower sensitivity to abrupt climate changes [CITATION_4] . Additionally, d",
